    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5ea09da5_31f5d083",
        "filename": "client/crash_report_database_win.cc",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 126,
      "author": {
        "id": 1143760
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-08-12T02:03:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Don’t add new fields to this structure, because it’ll change its layout on disk and break everyone’s existing metadata files. This is similar to the problem we had before where a new enum value was being introduced in the middle of existing values, changing everything’s meaning. Here are the options that I see:\n\n1. Stick this in ReportState by adding a new kPendingUploadExplicitlyRequested state there.\n2. “Steal” a reserved byte from padding[7], turning it to padding[6].\n3. Redefining “uploaded” to be a bitfield. You can do this because right now, it’s defined to only carry 0 or 1, so we can say that bit 0 of the new field (f \u0026 (1 \u003c\u003c 0)) is “uploaded”, and we can make bit 1 (f \u0026 (1 \u003c\u003c 1)) be “upload_explicitly_requested”.\n\nThe first option, which is what we were looking at before, is probably less desirable on the second thought because it’d be something that’s used in the on-disk representation, but ideally not something used in the in-memory representation. Since the two share an enum, it gets hairy.\n\nI kinda like the third choice because it keeps our options for future expansion options in this structure open pretty wide, since it leaves all of those existing 7 padding bits available for future use.",
      "revId": "e4bccefe071eb8569b692d047d29cbc249e57393",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": false
